perceiving the activity of fire in nature&#xD;<lb/>
its important effects and its vivifying agency&#xD;<lb/>
instead of collecting facts with regard to it in&#xD;<lb/>
the spirit of a true observer for the purpose&#xD;<lb/>
of ascertaining the general laws by which it&#xD;<lb/>
was governed -&#xD;<lb/>
P only assumed that it was the&#xD;<lb/>
principle of all things - And that Earth&#xD;<lb/>
and Air and water were only peculiar forms of&#xD;<lb/>
Heat -&#xD;<lb/>
