but details the opinions of the Philosophers who&#xD;<lb/>
had preceded him - He ballances opinions,&#xD;<lb/>
He discusses and analyses Hypotheses, and generally&#xD;<lb/>
leaves the mind in perfect indecision and&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in ignorance</hi> of the part that He himself had&#xD;<lb/>
taken in the question&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
27&#xD;<lb/>
The of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag64"
                ref="#otherwork_045"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag64">
            the Dialogues
        </bibl>
            </rs> |_ however |_ whatever view&#xD;<lb/>
may be taken is of a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">much higher</hi> Character than the&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Knowledge</hi>, and it is impossible not to regret that&#xD;<lb/>
such <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great talents</hi> were thrown away upon subjects&#xD;<lb/>
often of mere amusement and without utility or&#xD;<lb/>
any durable interest -&#xD;<lb/>
All the truly valuable discoveries that remain of&#xD;<lb/>
this distinguished man relates to mathematics&#xD;<lb/>
And in this department of science He certainly made&#xD;<lb/>
great progress which is the more astonishing when&#xD;<lb/>
the vividness of his fancy and the playful wildness&#xD;<lb/>
of his Mind are considered. -&#xD;<lb/>
It was in the School of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag65" ref="#person_085" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag65" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi> that the most&#xD;<lb/>
celebrated mathematicians of Antiquity were formed&#xD;<lb/>
and that the rudiments of the methods were&#xD;<lb/>
produced by which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in those later times</hi> the great&#xD;<lb/>
phenomena of the universe have been explained&#xD;<lb/>
and the laws of the motions of the Earth and&#xD;<lb/>
the Heavenly bodies ascertained&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
28&#xD;<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag66"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag66" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Aristotle</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> was the disciple of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag67"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag67" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs>, but the&#xD;<lb/>
character of his philosophy is wholly unlike that&#xD;<lb/>
of his master -&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag68"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag68" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs> attempted to raise science to the high flights&#xD;<lb/>
of poetry - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag69"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag69" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> on the contrary endeavoured&#xD;<lb/>
to bring poesy to fixed rules and to explain&#xD;<lb/>
the principles of eloquence. -&#xD;<lb/>
The <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag70"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag70" type="person">
          philosopher of Stagyra
        </name>
            </rs>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">truly conceived</hi>
            <lb/>
that one method was applicable to all the&#xD;<lb/>
departments of human knowledge but unfortunately&#xD;<lb/>
for the progress of science He himself did not&#xD;<lb/>
employ <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the true method</hi> He began with&#xD;<lb/>
generalizations and attempted to descend to&#xD;<lb/>
particulars and hence his conclusions were&#xD;<lb/>
almost always modified according to a&#xD;<lb/>
preconceived Theory.&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
29&#xD;<lb/>
The comprehensive mind and the extensive talents&#xD;<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag71"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag71" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> were employed upon all the subjects&#xD;<lb/>
of practical or speculative investigation and&#xD;<lb/>
when the range that He took is considered we&#xD;<lb/>
ought rather to wonder that He discovered truth&#xD;<lb/>
at all than to be su<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">p</del>prised that He discovered&#xD;<lb/>
it so rarely.&#xD;<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">physics</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag72"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag72" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> are perhaps the least&#xD;<lb/>
instructive of his works for He was not an&#xD;<lb/>
experimenter, and He was seldom contented to&#xD;<lb/>
adopt the opinions of Men who had gone&#xD;<lb/>
before him -&#xD;<lb/>
He has given very few correct explanations&#xD;<lb/>
and his notions on causes are perhaps less accurate&#xD;<lb/>
than those adopted in the Early Schools of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag73"
                ref="#place_167"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag73" type="place">
          Greece
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag74"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag74" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> asserted that the world was eternal&#xD;<lb/>
that the expanse of the sky was <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">spherical</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="32"
                xml:id="pb-32"
                facs="#i32"/>
            <lb/>
30&#xD;<lb/>
Spherical that the Earth was immortal and that the&#xD;<lb/>
stars were a part of the heavens and moving&#xD;<lb/>
only within the sphere in which they were fixd.&#xD;<lb/>
In <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag75"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag75" type="person">
          Aristotles
        </name>
            </rs> abstracted principles with regard to&#xD;<lb/>
the properties of matter there was a greater&#xD;<lb/>
opportunity for him to exert his powerful talents&#xD;<lb/>
And upon these subjects some of his notions&#xD;<lb/>
were tolerably correct. Thus He had an idea&#xD;<lb/>
of gravity as an uniform property of matter&#xD;<lb/>
and He contrasts it with levity, by which there&#xD;<lb/>
is some reason to suppose He meant a repulsive&#xD;<lb/>
force -&#xD;<lb/>
He conceived that the elements of bodies&#xD;<lb/>
were unknown to us in their real state and&#xD;<lb/>
that we were acquainted only with their&#xD;<lb/>
compounds -&#xD;<lb/>
And on this notion He produced his&#xD;<lb/>
Theory of actual and possible existence&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="33"
                xml:id="pb-33"
                facs="#i33"/>
            <lb/>
31&#xD;<lb/>
in which He conceived an essential species of matter&#xD;<lb/>
capable of assuming a great variety of forms&#xD;<lb/>
The most important of the works of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag76"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag76" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
in Natural Science is his history of Animals -&#xD;<lb/>
Here He found it impossible to indulge in vague&#xD;<lb/>
conjecture and his patience in registering minute&#xD;<lb/>
observations on this occasion is the most admirable&#xD;<lb/>
as his mind had generally been applied only to&#xD;<lb/>
the discovery of grand and striking analogies&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag77"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag77" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> was assisted by the riches and power&#xD;<lb/>
of his scholar <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag78"
                ref="#person_810"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag78" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Alexander the great</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> in the collection&#xD;<lb/>
of the specimens for this <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">work in Natural History</hi>
            <lb/>
And it has been supposed by some Writers that&#xD;<lb/>
the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag79"
                ref="#person_810"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag79" type="person">
          Macedonian Conqueror
        </name>
            </rs> in patronizing <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
