the light of knowledge the benefit of Arts&#xD;<lb/>
from the west to the East from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag81"
                ref="#place_167"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag81" type="place">
          Greece
        </name>
            </rs> to&#xD;<lb/>
every part of the Globe.&#xD;<lb/>
These ideas however certainly are delusive&#xD;<lb/>
Such bright visions might occasionally have&#xD;<lb/>
passed through his lofty and glowing Mind&#xD;<lb/>
but every trait of his Character proves that&#xD;<lb/>
the motive for all his great exertions was&#xD;<lb/>
an ungovernable Ambition an insatible&#xD;<lb/>
lust of power&#xD;<lb/>
To satisfy these His short life was devoted to&#xD;<lb/>
war and bloodshed and to satisfy these other&#xD;<lb/>
men were considered only as machines to&#xD;<lb/>
fulfil his purposes or to be sacrifised to&#xD;<lb/>
accomplish his views. -&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="35"
                xml:id="pb-35"
                facs="#i35"/>
            <lb/>
33&#xD;<lb/>
He cultivated letters but <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">then</add> it was from the desire of being&#xD;<lb/>
thought in all things and his address to&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag82"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag82" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> on the publication of his works proves that He&#xD;<lb/>
had <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">no</add> noble and abstracted love of truth and that&#xD;<lb/>
selfishness and vanity were the feelings that induced&#xD;<lb/>
him to promote the interests of learned Men.&#xD;<lb/>
Why have you published your works He says -&#xD;<lb/>
to wherein shall We be great if the learning in&#xD;<lb/>
which we were educated be made common to all -&#xD;<lb/>
And I wish to excell <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">others</hi> as much in Knowledge&#xD;<lb/>
as in power -&#xD;<lb/>
Theophrastus was the successor of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag83"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag83" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> in&#xD;<lb/>
the Lyceum and none of the ancients seem to&#xD;<lb/>
have studied Natural science with so much effect&#xD;<lb/>
I entered very fully upon his character in the&#xD;<lb/>
Geological lectures.&#xD;<lb/>
And I shall not run the risque of fatiguing&#xD;<lb/>
by goin over the same ground the second time&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="36"
                xml:id="pb-36"
                facs="#i36"/>
            <lb/>
34&#xD;<lb/>
This illustrious Character can scarcely be praised&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">too much</hi> but were I to dwell long on his merits&#xD;<lb/>
you would perhaps think that He might be&#xD;<lb/>
praised too often -&#xD;<lb/>
The speculative doctrines which issued from the&#xD;<lb/>
Schools of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag84"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag84" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag85" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> from the academy&#xD;<lb/>
and the Lyceum continued nearly for 1800 Years&#xD;<lb/>
to occupy and agitate the minds of men and&#xD;<lb/>
their influence was felt from the confines of&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag86"
                ref="#place_1212"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag86" type="place">
          Arabia
        </name>
            </rs> to the extremity of Europe -&#xD;<lb/>
Men of warm feelings and vivid passions in&#xD;<lb/>
whom the imagination was more active than their&#xD;<lb/>
reason were most disposed to adopt the enthusiastic&#xD;<lb/>
Theories stamped by the ardor of a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">poetic mind</hi>
            <lb/>
Persons of sounder and cooler judgments of a&#xD;<lb/>
turn for rigid criticism became attached to the&#xD;<lb/>
opinions and to the cyllogistic methods of&#xD;<lb/>
the stagyrite and the two systems for a long&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="37"
                xml:id="pb-37"
                facs="#i37"/>
            <lb/>
35&#xD;<lb/>
while divided between them the empire of the mind&#xD;<lb/>
Their influence was various both constantly&#xD;<lb/>
propagated errors and often assisted prejudice;&#xD;<lb/>
but they produced good effects by calling forth&#xD;<lb/>
the powers of men and by inducing them to&#xD;<lb/>
combat what appeared false opinion and they&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and</del> preserved the activity of the faculties through&#xD;<lb/>
an age of darkness and ignorance -&#xD;<lb/>
They made men acquainted with the forms of&#xD;<lb/>
reasoning. and when the authority of the&#xD;<lb/>
chair had passed away the method of discussion&#xD;<lb/>
which had long been applied to non entities was&#xD;<lb/>
made use of for explaining realities and the&#xD;<lb/>
doctrines of the scholars were overturned by&#xD;<lb/>
weapons which they themselves had formed&#xD;<lb/>
and truth was elevated at the same time&#xD;<lb/>
error was destroyed -&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="38"
                xml:id="pb-38"
                facs="#i38"/>
            <lb/>
36&#xD;<lb/>
At the time the great contests were taking&#xD;<lb/>
place between the successor of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag87"
                ref="#person_810"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag87" type="person">
          Alexander
        </name>
            </rs> and at&#xD;<lb/>
the turbulent period when so many different&#xD;<lb/>
