                rend="underline">whole force</hi> of his mind to the study&#xD;<lb/>
of the moving properties of bodies and to&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="39"
                xml:id="pb-39"
                facs="#i39"/>
            <lb/>
37&#xD;<lb/>
the explanation of them by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">numbers</hi> and&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">geometrical forms</hi> -&#xD;<lb/>
This genius appears to have been of the&#xD;<lb/>
first order and His discoveries are <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">abundant</del>
            <lb/>
undoubtedly the most splendid belonging to antiqu<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">ity</hi>
            <lb/>
He first ascertained the nature of the mechaniean&#xD;<lb/>
powers and the laws of Hydrostatics -&#xD;<lb/>
He constructed the first planetarium&#xD;<lb/>
He was acquainted with the powers of burning&#xD;<lb/>
mirrors and we owe to his talents some of the&#xD;<lb/>
highest refinements of the methods of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mathematical</del>
            <lb/>
Mathematical investigation&#xD;<lb/>
The effects of the inventions of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag89"
                ref="#person_417"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag89" type="person">
          Archimedes
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
were such as we are even unable to produce&#xD;<lb/>
in modern times&#xD;<lb/>
An interesting account is given by <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Plutar<hi rend="superscript">ch</hi>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
