                xml:id="ttag92"
                ref="#place_936"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag92" type="place">
          Syracuse
        </name>
            </rs> against the&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">romans</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="40"
                xml:id="pb-40"
                facs="#i40"/>
            <lb/>
38&#xD;<lb/>
The history is very interesting and contains many&#xD;<lb/>
curious particulars of the studies of this great&#xD;<lb/>
man and some refined observations on <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">his</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Character -</hi>
            <lb/>
The subject is treated with a freshness of&#xD;<lb/>
memory and so striking a delineation of&#xD;<lb/>
incident that I shall venture to read a long&#xD;<lb/>
extract.&#xD;<lb/>
