as to be perhaps incapable of improvement and&#xD;<lb/>
which present one of the few finished productions&#xD;<lb/>
of the human mind&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="52"
                xml:id="pb-52"
                facs="#i52"/>
            <lb/>
50&#xD;<lb/>
It was in the school of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag125"
                ref="#place_1135"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag125" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
            </rs> that&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag126"
                ref="#person_914"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag126" type="person">
          Aristarchus
        </name>
            </rs> endeavoured to revive the idea&#xD;<lb/>
the notion of the earth - and to measure the&#xD;<lb/>
distance of the Sun and He concluded that&#xD;<lb/>
this luminary was about 20 times farther&#xD;<lb/>
from us than the Moon an estimation <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">though</del>
            <lb/>
which though incorrect still enlarged the ideas&#xD;<lb/>
of men with regard to the extent of the&#xD;<lb/>
Universe.&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag127"
                ref="#person_915"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag127" type="person">
          Eratosthenes
        </name>
            </rs> who succeeded <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag128"
                ref="#person_914"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag128" type="person">
          Aristarchus
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
followed a similar path of observation and&#xD;<lb/>
ascertained the obliquity of the Ecliptic at&#xD;<lb/>
that time a discovery <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the utmost importance</hi>
            <lb/>
for the progress of the Science&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="53"
                xml:id="pb-53"
                facs="#i53"/>
            <lb/>
51&#xD;<lb/>
But of all the Astronomers of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag129"
                ref="#place_1135"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag129" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag130"
                ref="#person_916"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag130" type="person">
          Hipparchus
        </name>
            </rs> -&#xD;<lb/>
was the person who made the greatest number of&#xD;<lb/>
observations&#xD;<lb/>
He formed the first table of the Sun - He determined&#xD;<lb/>
the time of the revolution of the Moon and ascertain<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">d</add>
            <lb/>
the nature of her orbit.&#xD;<lb/>
And He made a labourious catalogue of the fixed&#xD;<lb/>
stars which seems to have been executed with the&#xD;<lb/>
greatest accuracy and precision&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag131"
                ref="#person_737"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag131" type="person">
          Potolemy
        </name>
            </rs> the last philosopher of the Greek&#xD;<lb/>
school of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag132"
                ref="#place_1135"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag132" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
            </rs> flourished about 200 years&#xD;<lb/>
after <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag133"
                ref="#person_916"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag133" type="person">
          Hipparchus
        </name>
            </rs> - in the 130 year of the Christian&#xD;<lb/>
era - He collected all the observations of his&#xD;<lb/>
predecessor and added to them a number of new&#xD;<lb/>
ones - He endeavoured to establish a system of&#xD;<lb/>
planetary motions by supposing the Earth in&#xD;<lb/>
the centre and the sun the moon and the&#xD;<lb/>
stars revolving round it&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="54"
                xml:id="pb-54"
                facs="#i54"/>
            <lb/>
52&#xD;<lb/>
but though this part of his doctrine is&#xD;<lb/>
incorrect yet his account of the phenomena&#xD;<lb/>
is elegant and precise -&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag134"
                ref="#person_737"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag134" type="person">
          Potolemy
        </name>
            </rs> attempted in his <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag135"
                ref="#otherwork_251"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag135">
            Almagest
        </bibl>
            </rs> a&#xD;<lb/>
complete theory of astronomy - It still exists&#xD;<lb/>
and is one of the most precious of the monumen<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ts</add>
            <lb/>
of Antiquity -&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">The ideas</hi> which he adopted were current&#xD;<lb/>
for nearly 1400 years - late discoveries have&#xD;<lb/>
proved them to be erroneous; but it must not&#xD;<lb/>
be forgotten that they led the moderns to the&#xD;<lb/>
investigation of truth and that they were&#xD;<lb/>
in the dark ages the only foundation&#xD;<lb/>
of the science. -&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="55"
                xml:id="pb-55"
                facs="#i55"/>
            <lb/>
53&#xD;<lb/>
From the general tenour of what has been advanced&#xD;<lb/>
and particularly from all the later instances it&#xD;<lb/>
is evident that whenever the greek Philosophers&#xD;<lb/>
were contented with reasoning upon their observati<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ons</add>
            <lb/>
the results of Theory obtained were always opposite&#xD;<lb/>
and often grand and conformable to the facts&#xD;<lb/>
of nature; but in their speculations that remain&#xD;<lb/>
concerning the general system of things no&#xD;<lb/>
distinct or extensive truths ever occur and the&#xD;<lb/>
semblances of truths in their hypotheses seem&#xD;<lb/>
rather to have been the result of accident&#xD;<lb/>
than of any peculiarity or the correctness of&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">by which</del> the method by which the were formed&#xD;<lb/>
- Still however <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">their</hi> views of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">material</hi> existence&#xD;<lb/>
I mean the views <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of their most</hi> distinguished&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">masters</hi> often present a sublimity of thought&#xD;<lb/>
and a grandeur of expression which demonstrate&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="56"
                xml:id="pb-56"
                facs="#i56"/>
            <lb/>
54&#xD;<lb/>
the warm imagination and the power of the mind&#xD;<lb/>
by which they were created - |_ We may purcieve&#xD;<lb/>
in them a character which marks the ardour&#xD;<lb/>
of curiosity and the restlessness of lofty <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Genius</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">which</hi> despising the slow methods of acquiring&#xD;<lb/>
knowledge offered by the senses by minute <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">observa</del>
            <lb/>
observations and laborious experiment endeavours&#xD;<lb/>
to approve its unassisted strength to obstacles and&#xD;<lb/>
difficulties; and unable either to lift up or&#xD;<lb/>
to rend the veil that conceals the Mysteries&#xD;<lb/>
of Nature and exhausted by its own efforts&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sleeps</hi> and dreams that it has penetrated&#xD;<lb/>
even into the very sanctuary of her temper. -&#xD;<lb/>
The perfection of the execution of the&#xD;<lb/>
philosophical literature of the Greeks likewise&#xD;<lb/>
has a claim to our high admiration.&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="57"
                xml:id="pb-57"
                facs="#i57"/>
            <lb/>
55&#xD;<lb/>
The refinement of their taste is demonstrated by&#xD;<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">graces</hi> of their stile by its dignity&#xD;<lb/>
simplicity, and energy.&#xD;<lb/>
No people perhaps ever understood <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">so distinctly</hi>
            <lb/>
the principles of the sublime the beautiful&#xD;<lb/>
the decorous -&#xD;<lb/>
The principles appear even in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">their</del>
            <lb/>
their <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">arroneous</del> erroneous sientific Histories and&#xD;<lb/>
shine forth amidst the obscurity of error and&#xD;<lb/>
of doubt - and give an interest and an effect&#xD;<lb/>
to combinations of thoughts which otherwise would&#xD;<lb/>
have appeared triffling and <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">inseg</del> insignificant&#xD;<lb/>
In their descriptions and even in their analogies&#xD;<lb/>
every thing is chaste and properly disposed no&#xD;<lb/>
meretricious Arts are adopted - no attempts are made&#xD;<lb/>
to enhance the sublime or the beautiful by causing&#xD;<lb/>
it to follow <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the ludicrous</hi> -&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="58"
                xml:id="pb-58"
                facs="#i58"/>
            <lb/>
56&#xD;<lb/>
no efforts are made to blend together incongruous&#xD;<lb/>
forms for the mere amusement of the fancy&#xD;<lb/>
Elegance and decorum and greatness are the&#xD;<lb/>
elements of the interest they produce:&#xD;<lb/>
And the remains of the sientific systems of the&#xD;<lb/>
greeks like the ruins of their magnificent&#xD;<lb/>
edifices must excite atonishment and admiration&#xD;<lb/>
even though their systems were formed by false&#xD;<lb/>
speculations though their temples were devoted&#xD;<lb/>
to Idolatry. -&#xD;<lb/>
The perfection of the language of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag136"
                ref="#place_167"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag136" type="place">
          Greece
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
might at first view be considered as having&#xD;<lb/>
been rather favourable than detrimental to&#xD;<lb/>
the progress of physical Science: but a&#xD;<lb/>
correct examination of the subject I am&#xD;<lb/>
inclined to believe would <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">ad</del> lead to <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del> a&#xD;<lb/>
different opinion the enquiry is one of&#xD;<lb/>
great importance and it surely will not&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="59"
                xml:id="pb-59"
                facs="#i59"/>
            <lb/>
57&#xD;<lb/>
be improper to enter upon some general views&#xD;<lb/>
with regard to it on this occasion -&#xD;<lb/>
Every language is in its simplest state either&#xD;<lb/>
an expression of feelings or of things and all&#xD;<lb/>
the words belonging to it in their original&#xD;<lb/>
construction are that signify simple objects&#xD;<lb/>
or simple Ideas.&#xD;<lb/>
Abstractions are only gradually formed&#xD;<lb/>
when one word is made to imply a number of&#xD;<lb/>
other <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">words which</hi> themselves denote things&#xD;<lb/>
and it is on abstractions or general terms&#xD;<lb/>
that all scientific proposition depends&#xD;<lb/>
When accurate <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">views</hi> are <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">taken</del> represented&#xD;<lb/>
in general <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">proportions</hi> there is always an&#xD;<lb/>
immediate recurrence to the simpler words&#xD;<lb/>
that they represent and hence the appeal <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">is</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to relations of facts</hi> and the feelings of assent&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="60"
                xml:id="pb-60"
                facs="#i60"/>
            <lb/>
58&#xD;<lb/>
or dissent when first formed and founded upon&#xD;<lb/>
the distinct <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">connections</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">words</hi> and things&#xD;<lb/>
But in the progress of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">acquisition</del>
            <lb/>
acquisition and the use of language after&#xD;<lb/>
a certain number of propositions are&#xD;<lb/>
understood they become axioms and are&#xD;<lb/>
employed for conveniency and expedition&#xD;<lb/>
independently of facts as methods of opinion&#xD;<lb/>
It is on this circumstance that the most&#xD;<lb/>
refined of our reasons are formed.&#xD;<lb/>
and that the great use of language as&#xD;<lb/>
an instrument of thought depends -&#xD;<lb/>
But it is likewise on this circumstance&#xD;<lb/>
that a number of erroneous conclusions&#xD;<lb/>
of prejudices and of false theories are&#xD;<lb/>
established and cloaked as it were in&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="61"
                xml:id="pb-61"
                facs="#i61"/>
            <lb/>
59&#xD;<lb/>
the forms which ought only to express truth&#xD;<lb/>
when the natural order of association is&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">strictly followed</hi> no mistakes can arise from&#xD;<lb/>
the use of general propositions&#xD;<lb/>
but when abstracted words have been&#xD;<lb/>
exceedingly multiplied it becomes deficient&#xD;<lb/>
to define the<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">ir</del> true signification of all&#xD;<lb/>
and yet from their having been employed&#xD;<lb/>
habitually, they produce a great effect upon&#xD;<lb/>
the mind and become connected with strong&#xD;<lb/>
and vivid feelings.&#xD;<lb/>
All the physical writings of the greeks&#xD;<lb/>
demonstrate that terms of this kind without&#xD;<lb/>
any distinct meaning had continually <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">accum</del>
            <lb/>
accumulated in their language and that in&#xD;<lb/>
proportion even as it became more <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">harmon</del>
            <lb/>
harmonious more energetic and more copious&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="62"
                xml:id="pb-62"
                facs="#i62"/>
            <lb/>
60&#xD;<lb/>
Applied to the phenomena of nature they&#xD;<lb/>
were often made the foundations of theories;&#xD;<lb/>
and where the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primitive materials</hi> were&#xD;<lb/>
of so loose and incoherent a species it necessarily&#xD;<lb/>
followed that the superstructure however&#xD;<lb/>
beautiful <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">or grand</hi> never possesses solidity&#xD;<lb/>
or convenience or permanency. -&#xD;<lb/>
The correctness the excellency of the style&#xD;<lb/>
of the most eminent of the grecian Philosophers&#xD;<lb/>
are worthy of our highest praise and deserving&#xD;<lb/>
our zealous imitation&#xD;<lb/>
But never may we desert the sublime&#xD;<lb/>
methods of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag137"
                ref="#person_124"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag137" type="person">
          Bacon
        </name>
            </rs> and of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag138"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag138" type="person">
          Newton
        </name>
            </rs> for the rules&#xD;<lb/>
of the speculative philosophy developed by&#xD;<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag139"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag139" type="person">
          Plato
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag140"
                ref="#person_138"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag140" type="person">
          Aristotle
        </name>
            </rs> never may we relinquish&#xD;<lb/>
the pure <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">troths</del> truths of modern science&#xD;<lb/>
which are images of nature for the&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="63"
                xml:id="pb-63"
                facs="#i63"/>
            <lb/>
61&#xD;<lb/>
speculations of Elder times which are the fancies&#xD;<lb/>
of men&#xD;<lb/>
In all cases in science it is our business&#xD;<lb/>
to analyse every principle and to ascertain&#xD;<lb/>
to what expressions of facts it relates or to&#xD;<lb/>
what simpler laws it may be referred -&#xD;<lb/>
It is our duty to separate propositions from&#xD;<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">human</del> human passions and to reason on&#xD;<lb/>
them as mere representation of things and&#xD;<lb/>
to employ no terms that are either perplexed&#xD;<lb/>
or doubtful or uncommon&#xD;<lb/>
The same processes of thought ever will&#xD;<lb/>
apply in common life as in science -&#xD;<lb/>
experience must be our only guide - Experience&#xD;<lb/>
or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">moral feeling</hi> founded on accurate and&#xD;<lb/>
distinct knowledge&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="64"
                xml:id="pb-64"
                facs="#i64"/>
            <lb/>
62&#xD;<lb/>
Words alone must never be suffered to satisfy&#xD;<lb/>
or fill the mind and their relations to&#xD;<lb/>
facts must be ascertained before they can be&#xD;<lb/>
considered either of importance or of use&#xD;<lb/>
The imagination must be subjected&#xD;<lb/>
to the judgment or rather they must naturally&#xD;<lb/>
operate and assist and correct each other.&#xD;<lb/>
We may be always safely entertained by wit&#xD;<lb/>
We may always be safely delighted by eloquence&#xD;<lb/>
for they are the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">life</hi> and the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">organs</hi> of the&#xD;<lb/>
mind: -&#xD;<lb/>
But never let us consider wit as argument&#xD;<lb/>
or eloquence as truth till we have cooly&#xD;<lb/>
examined them by the test of right <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">reason</hi>
            <lb/>
for this is the only certain guide of&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="65"
                xml:id="pb-65"
                facs="#i65"/>
            <lb/>
63&#xD;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">opinion</hi> a principle the same in all&#xD;<lb/>
ages and in all matters independent&#xD;<lb/>
of fashion or caprice unchanging&#xD;<lb/>
immortal. -&#xD;<lb/>
            <lb/>
